{{Spanish name|Verástegui|Peláez}} {{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Enrique Verástegui | honorific_suffix = | image = Enrique_Verástegui.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Enrique Verástegui in 2011 | birth_name = | birth_date = 24 April 1950 | birth_place = [[Lima]], [[Perú]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2018|07|27|1950|4|24}} | death_place = Lima, Perú | death_cause = | nationality = | citizenship = | alma_mater = [[National University of San Marcos]] | occupation = Economist, poet, essayist, philosopher, storyteller, novelist, playwright, scriptwriter, musician, watercolorist, physicist, logician and mathematician |awards=[[Guggenheim Fellowship]] |spouse=Carmen Ollé<ref>[https://larepublica.pe/cultural/1289243-enrique-verastegui-temporada-arequipa-testimonio Enrique Verástegui, una temporada en Arequipa (testimonio)] {{es icon}}</ref> |children=Vanessa Verástegui Ollé }} '''Enrique Fidel Verástegui Peláez ''' (24 April 1950 – 27 July 2018), was a Peruvian author and mathematician. With his first book, ''In the extramural of the world'' (1971), he was regarded as one of the most important poets of Latin America<ref name="telesurtv">{{cite web|url=https://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/Peruvian-Rebel-Poet-Enrique-Verastegui-Dead-at-68-20180728-0012.html|title=Peruvian Rebel Poet Enrique Verastegui Dies Aged 68 &#124; News &#124; teleSUR English|website=telesurtv.net|accessdate=2018-08-02}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080508204248/http://www.educared.edu.pe/estudiantes/literatura/verastegui.htm Poemas de Enrique Verástegui] {{es icon}}</ref> and co-founded the Zero Hour Movement, together with the poets: Jorge Pimentel, Juan Ramírez Ruiz, Jorge Nájar, Enriqueta Belevan and Carmen Ollé.<ref>[https://elcomercio.pe/luces/libros/enrique-verastegui-poeta-peruano-reconocido-fallecio-68-anos-noticia-540859 Reconocido poeta peruano Enrique Verástegui falleció a los 68 años] {{es icon}}</ref><ref>[http://christianul.blogspot.com/2012/11/entrevista-enrique-verastegui-por-raul.html ENTREVISTA A ENRIQUE VERÁSTEGUI POR RAÚL HERAUD.] {{es icon}}</ref>
He was born on 24 April 1950 in the city of [[Lima]], but grew up in the city of [[San Vicente de Cañete]]. He finished his secondary studies at G.U.E. José Buenaventura Sepúlveda of said city.<ref>[http://rpp.pe/cultura/literatura/la-poesia-peruana-de-luto-fallecio-enrique-verastegui-noticia-1139653 La poesía peruana de luto: Falleció Enrique Verástegui] {{es icon}}</ref> Moved to Lima, he studied economics, administration and accounting at the National University of San Marcos. In 1975 he recorded his poems for the [[Library of Congress|Library of Congress of the United States]] and worked for [[El Colegio de México]].<ref>[https://www.ecured.cu/Enrique_Ver%C3%A1stegui Enrique Verástegui.] {{es icon}}</ref> On 1976 he received the [[Guggenheim Fellowship]].<ref>[http://www.serperuano.com/2017/04/enrique-verastegui/ Enrique Fidel Verástegui] {{es icon}}</ref>
In 1977, he founded Hora Zero Internacional in Paris with José Carlos Rodríguez and André Laude and writes his book ''The Motor of Desire'' (''El motor del deseo'').<ref>[http://cartoneracohuina.blogspot.com/2014/08/entrevista-enrique-verastegui-por-paul.html Entrevista a Enrique Verástegui por Paul Guillén] {{es icon}}</ref> In 1978, representing the [[Peru]]vian community, he reads his poems before the tomb of [[César Vallejo]], which earned him the congratulations of [[Julio Ramón Ribeyro]], consul of Peru to [[UNESCO]]. In 1992 he published his novel trilogy, entitled ''Terceto de Lima''. In 1999 he wrote ''Pro-total Apology: Essay on Stephen Hawkings'', the Peruvian equivalent of the ''[[Novum Organum]]'' by [[Francis Bacon]], which suggests original developments of algebra, and which is recommended by the Library of Congress of the United States. He also invents the Scientific Research Method of pre-duction, which is superior to induction and the deduction. He also publishes ''El Modelo del Teorema'' (''The model of the theorem'').<ref>[https://lancomperu.wordpress.com/2013/11/15/enrique-fidel-verastegui-pelaez-referencias/ Enrique Fidel Verástegui Peláez, referencias] {{es icon}}</ref>
